    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Corzine and Reform</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan Schoffman letter says June 8 editorial unfairly singled out Jon S Corzine, Senate candidate in New Jersey, as having a special obligation to change the campaign finance system</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''New Jersey's Excessive Senate Race'' (editorial, June 8) singles out Jon S. Corzine as having a special obligation to change the campaign finance system that helped him win. Why should he be more obligated than any others who run for office?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''New Jersey's Excessive Senate Race'' (editorial, June 8) singles out Jon S. Corzine as having a special obligation to change the campaign finance system that helped him win. Why should he be more obligated than any others who run for office?</p>
        <p>Complete overhaul of the system is long overdue, but I feel safer with a candidate spending his own money than with the vast majority of officeholders who must spend time raising money and are therefore beholden to special interest groups. It would indeed be ironic if campaign finance reform was spurred to fruition because of this ''threat'' to incumbents.</p>
        <p>ALAN SCHOFFMAN  Teaneck, N.J., June 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
